VALUES
(44, 1, 23, 44, 15, 22, 22, 'Barsabas', 'Connection of Names in Acts', 'This connection highlights the use of the name ''Barsabas'' in both passages, linking Joseph called Barsabas in Acts 1:23 to Judas surnamed Barsabas in Acts 15:22. Both passages emphasize the significance of chosen individuals within the early church.', 'keyword', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 23, 44, 1, 26, 26, NULL, 'Appointment of Matthias', 'Both passages emphasize the selection of Matthias as an apostle. The first verse introduces Matthias as one of the two candidates, while the second confirms his appointment through the casting of lots.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 24, 9, 16, 7, 7, 'which knowest the hearts of all men', 'Connection of Heart Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize that the Lord knows the hearts of individuals. Acts 1:24 asks God to reveal His choice based on this heart knowledge, while 1 Samuel 16:7 states that the Lord looks on the heart, not outward appearances.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 24, 44, 15, 8, 8, 'which knowest the hearts', 'Connection of Divine Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize God''s knowledge of hearts, highlighting His role in discerning choices and granting the Holy Spirit. This connection underscores the divine authority in guiding believers.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 24, 24, 17, 10, 10, 'Thou, Lord, which knowest the hearts', 'Divine Knowledge of Hearts', 'Both passages emphasize God''s knowledge of human hearts. Acts 1:24 speaks of the Lord knowing hearts, while Jeremiah 17:10 declares that the Lord searches the heart. This connection highlights the theme of divine insight into human intentions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 24, 58, 4, 13, 13, 'Thou, Lord, which knowest the hearts', 'Divine Knowledge of Hearts', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s omniscience regarding human hearts. Both passages emphasize that all things are known and revealed in God''s sight.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 24, 44, 14, 23, 23, 'prayed', 'Prayer and Divine Guidance', 'Both passages emphasize the act of prayer in seeking God''s guidance. In Acts 1:24, the apostles pray for divine choice, while in Acts 14:23, they pray and fast before appointing elders, showing a consistent theme of reliance on God in decision-making.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 24, 66, 2, 23, 23, 'which knowest the hearts of all men', 'Connection of Heart Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God knowing the hearts of individuals. Acts 1:24 speaks of the Lord knowing the hearts of all men, while Revelation 2:23 mentions searching the reins and hearts, highlighting God''s omniscience regarding human intentions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 24, 45, 8, 27, 27, 'knowest the hearts of all men', 'Connection of Heart Knowledge', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s knowledge of human hearts. Both passages emphasize that God understands the inner thoughts and intentions of individuals, whether in choosing leaders or interceding for believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 25, 46, 9, 2, 2, 'apostleship', 'Apostleship and Ministry Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of apostleship, as both passages refer to the role and significance of apostles in the early church. Acts 1:25 discusses the transition of apostleship after Judas'' fall, while 1 Corinthians 9:2 emphasizes the validity of Paul''s apostleship through the believers he has ministered to.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 25, 43, 6, 70, 71, 'from which Judas by transgression fell', 'Connection of Judas Iscariot', 'Both passages emphasize Judas''s role as a betrayer. Acts refers to Judas''s transgression and his fall from apostleship, while John identifies him as ''a devil'' among the chosen twelve.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 25, 43, 17, 12, 12, 'that he might go to his own place', 'Connection of Betrayal and Loss', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of loss associated with Judas. Acts 1:25 refers to Judas''s transgression and his departure from the apostleship, while John 17:12 identifies him as the ''son of perdition,'' highlighting his ultimate fate.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 25, 45, 1, 5, 5, 'apostleship', 'Connection of Apostleship Themes', 'This connection highlights the concept of apostleship as a significant role within the early church. Both passages emphasize the importance of apostleship in spreading faith and ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 25, 44, 1, 16, 21, 'from which Judas by transgression fell', 'Connection of Judas'' Fall', 'Both passages emphasize Judas'' transgression and the consequences of his actions. Acts 1:25 refers to Judas'' fall from apostleship, while Acts 1:16-21 recounts the fulfillment of scripture regarding his betrayal and demise.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 25, 48, 2, 8, 8, 'apostleship', 'Apostleship and Ministry Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of apostleship in both passages. Acts 1:25 discusses the ministry and apostleship following Judas'' fall, while Galatians 2:8 emphasizes the apostleship of Peter and Paul, indicating a shared divine empowerment for their respective missions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 25, 13, 10, 13, 14, 'transgression fell', 'Transgression and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of transgression leading to downfall in both passages. Judas and Saul both faced dire consequences for their actions against the Lord, emphasizing the seriousness of their sins.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 26, 3, 16, 8, 8, NULL, 'Casting Lots for Divine Selection', 'This connection highlights the practice of casting lots as a means of divine decision-making in both passages. In Acts, the apostles cast lots to select Matthias, paralleling Aaron''s casting of lots to determine the fate of the goats in Leviticus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 26, 6, 18, 10, 10, NULL, 'Casting Lots for Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the practice of casting lots as a means of seeking divine guidance in decision-making. Both passages emphasize the act of casting lots to determine God''s will, whether in selecting Matthias as an apostle or dividing the land among the Israelites.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 26, 9, 14, 41, 42, 'gave forth their lots', 'Casting Lots for Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the act of casting lots to determine God''s choice for leadership. In Acts, Matthias is chosen among the apostles, while in 1 Samuel, Saul uses lots to select between himself and Jonathan.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 26, 32, 1, 7, 7, NULL, 'Casting Lots for Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the practice of casting lots to determine God''s will. Both passages depict the act of casting lots, resulting in a chosen individual, Matthias in Acts and Jonah in Jonah.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 26, 13, 24, 5, 5, 'gave forth their lots', 'Divine Selection by Lot', 'This connection highlights the practice of selecting individuals by lot, as seen in both passages. Acts 1:26 describes the apostles choosing Matthias through lots, paralleling 1 Chronicles 24:5, which details divisions made by lot among the priests.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 26, 44, 2, 14, 14, 'with the eleven', 'Connection of Apostolic Unity', 'Both passages emphasize the unity of the apostles. In Acts 1:26, Matthias is added to the eleven apostles, and in Acts 2:14, Peter stands with the eleven, highlighting their collective role in the early church.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 26, 20, 16, 22, 22, NULL, 'Wisdom and Decision-Making', 'This connection highlights the importance of understanding in making decisions, as seen in both passages. In Acts, the apostles seek divine guidance through lots, while Proverbs emphasizes that understanding leads to life, contrasting with folly.', 'theme', 0.293, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 1, 45, 15, 6, 6, 'with one accord', 'Unity in Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of unity among believers. Both passages emphasize being ''with one accord'' and ''one mind,'' indicating a collective purpose in glorifying God.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 1, 50, 2, 2, 2, NULL, 'Unity in Spirit and Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize being ''of one accord,'' highlighting the importance of unity among believers. Acts describes the early church''s unity at Pentecost, while Philippians encourages the same mindset among the church in Philippi.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 1, 44, 1, 13, 15, 'with one accord', 'Unity in Prayer and Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize being ''with one accord'' as the disciples gather in unity. This connection highlights the importance of communal prayer and preparation leading up to the outpouring of the Holy Spirit at Pentecost.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 1, 50, 1, 27, 27, 'one accord', 'Unity in Spirit and Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of unity among believers. Both passages emphasize being ''with one accord'' and ''one spirit,'' indicating a shared commitment to the gospel.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 1, 46, 16, 8, 8, 'Pentecost', 'Connection through Pentecost Timing', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Pentecost. Acts 2:1 describes the arrival of Pentecost, while 1 Corinthians 16:8 indicates a planned delay until Pentecost, highlighting its importance in the early church.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 1, 36, 3, 9, 9, 'with one accord', 'Unity in Worship and Language', 'This connection highlights the theme of unity in worship, as both passages emphasize being ''with one accord'' and serving ''with one consent.'' The call for a ''pure language'' in Zephaniah aligns with the idea of a unified community in Acts.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 1, 44, 4, 32, 32, 'one accord', 'Unity in Early Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of unity among believers. Both passages emphasize being ''of one accord'' and ''of one heart and of one soul,'' illustrating the communal spirit that characterized the early church.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 2, 44, 4, 31, 31, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize a powerful manifestation of the Holy Spirit. In Acts 2:2, the sound of a rushing mighty wind signifies the arrival of the Holy Spirit, while Acts 4:31 describes a place being shaken, indicating a similar divine presence and empowerment.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 2, 11, 19, 11, 11, 'rushing mighty wind', 'Connection of Divine Wind', 'Both passages emphasize a powerful wind as a manifestation of God''s presence. In Acts, the ''rushing mighty wind'' signifies the Holy Spirit, while in 1 Kings, the wind precedes God''s revelation, highlighting the divine nature of these events.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 2, 19, 18, 10, 10, 'rushing mighty wind', 'Connection of Wind Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of wind as a powerful force. In Acts, the ''rushing mighty wind'' signifies divine presence, while in Psalms, the ''wings of the wind'' illustrate God''s majestic movement.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 2, 43, 3, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Wind and Spirit', 'This connection highlights the imagery of wind as a representation of the Spirit. Both passages emphasize the mysterious and powerful nature of the wind, linking it to the work of the Holy Spirit in the lives of believers.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 2, 44, 16, 25, 26, 'suddenly', 'Divine Intervention in Crisis', 'Both passages emphasize sudden divine actions that lead to significant changes. In Acts 2, a sound from heaven signifies the arrival of the Holy Spirit, while in Acts 16, an earthquake results in the liberation of Paul and Silas and the prisoners.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 2, 23, 65, 24, 24, NULL, 'Divine Response and Presence', 'Both passages emphasize God''s immediate response to human actions. In Acts, the sound signifies God''s presence, while Isaiah highlights God''s readiness to answer before calls are made.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 2, 26, 3, 12, 13, 'rushing mighty wind', 'Connection of Rushing Sounds', 'Both passages emphasize a ''great rushing'' sound that signifies the presence of the divine. This connection highlights the powerful manifestation of God''s spirit in both instances.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 3, 40, 3, 11, 11, 'like as of fire', 'Connection of Fire Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fire as a transformative element. In Acts, the cloven tongues like fire signify the presence of the Holy Spirit, while in Matthew, the baptism with fire indicates a purifying and empowering work of the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 3, 43, 1, 32, 33, NULL, 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the descent of the Spirit. In Acts, the Spirit appears as cloven tongues of fire, while in John, it descends like a dove. This connection highlights the transformative presence of the Holy Spirit in both instances.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 3, 24, 23, 29, 29, 'like as of fire', 'Connection of Fire Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of fire in both passages. Acts 2:3 describes cloven tongues like fire, while Jeremiah 23:29 refers to God''s word as fire, emphasizing the transformative power of divine communication.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 3, 23, 11, 2, 3, NULL, 'Connection of the Spirit''s Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of the Spirit. Acts describes the Spirit appearing as ''cloven tongues like as of fire,'' while Isaiah speaks of the Spirit resting upon a figure, indicating divine empowerment and wisdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 3, 42, 24, 32, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Burning Hearts', 'Both passages emphasize a burning sensation associated with divine communication. In Acts, the ''cloven tongues like as of fire'' signify the presence of the Holy Spirit, while in Luke, the burning hearts reflect the impact of Jesus'' words on the disciples.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 3, 44, 2, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Holy Spirit and Tongues', 'This connection highlights the manifestation of the Holy Spirit through the appearance of ''cloven tongues'' and the subsequent act of speaking in ''other tongues.'' Both passages emphasize the transformative power of the Holy Spirit in enabling communication.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 3, 1, 11, 6, 6, NULL, 'Unity and Divine Intervention', 'This connection highlights the theme of unity among people and divine intervention. In Genesis, the Lord observes the people''s singular language and ambition, while in Acts, the appearance of cloven tongues signifies a new form of communication and unity among believers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 4, 41, 16, 17, 17, 'speak with other tongues', 'Connection of Speaking in Tongues', 'Both passages emphasize the act of speaking with new tongues as a sign of the Holy Spirit''s presence and empowerment in believers. This connection highlights the continuity of the promise of speaking in tongues from Jesus'' words to the fulfillment seen in Acts.', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 4, 44, 13, 52, 52, 'filled with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Holy Spirit Influence', 'Both passages emphasize being filled with the Holy Ghost, highlighting the transformative power of the Spirit in the lives of believers. The joy in Acts 13:52 can be seen as a result of this filling, connecting the experiences of the early disciples.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 4, 44, 4, 31, 31, 'filled with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Holy Spirit Filling', 'Both passages emphasize being filled with the Holy Ghost, highlighting a continuity of divine empowerment. In each instance, this filling leads to bold proclamation, demonstrating the transformative effect of the Spirit.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 4, 49, 5, 18, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Filling', 'Both passages emphasize being filled with the Spirit. Acts describes the initial filling that empowers speech, while Ephesians encourages continual filling for living wisely.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 4, 46, 12, 10, 10, 'other tongues', 'Connection of Tongues in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''divers kinds of tongues'' as seen in both passages. Acts 2:4 describes the initial outpouring of the Holy Spirit, leading to speaking in tongues, while 1 Corinthians 12:10 lists this phenomenon as a spiritual gift.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 4, 46, 14, 21, 23, 'other tongues', 'Connection of Tongues and Signs', 'Both passages emphasize the phenomenon of speaking with ''other tongues'' as a sign. Acts describes the initial occurrence of this event, while 1 Corinthians explains its purpose in relation to unbelievers.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 4, 43, 14, 26, 26, 'Holy Ghost', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the role of the Holy Ghost in empowering believers. Both passages emphasize the Holy Ghost''s function in teaching and enabling communication.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 5, 42, 2, 25, 25, 'devout men', 'Devout Men in Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of devout individuals in Jerusalem. Acts 2:5 mentions ''devout men'' while Luke 2:25 describes Simeon as ''just and devout,'' highlighting a theme of piety in the city.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 5, 44, 8, 2, 2, 'devout men', 'Devout Men in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize ''devout men'' who play significant roles in their respective contexts. In Acts 2:5, devout men gather in Jerusalem, while in Acts 8:2, they mourn Stephen''s death, highlighting their commitment to faith.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 5, 51, 1, 23, 23, 'under heaven', 'Connection of Preaching to All Nations', 'This connection highlights the theme of the gospel being preached to all people. Both passages mention the phrase ''under heaven,'' emphasizing the universal reach of the message.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 5, 2, 23, 16, 16, NULL, 'Harvest and Gathering Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of gathering, as both passages reference the gathering of people or produce. Acts 2:5 mentions Jews from every nation, paralleling Exodus 23:16''s focus on the ingathering of harvest.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 5, 5, 2, 25, 25, 'every nation under heaven', 'Fear of Nations Under Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of nations under heaven. Acts 2:5 mentions Jews from every nation, while Deuteronomy 2:25 speaks of nations under the whole heaven experiencing dread. This connection highlights the universal scope of God''s influence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 5, 23, 66, 18, 18, 'every nation under heaven', 'Gathering of Nations', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of people from various nations. Acts 2:5 mentions Jews from ''every nation under heaven,'' while Isaiah 66:18 speaks of gathering ''all nations and tongues.'' This connection highlights the inclusivity of God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 5, 38, 8, 18, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of God speaking to His people. Acts 2:5 highlights the gathering of devout Jews, while Zechariah 8:18 introduces a message from the Lord, indicating divine engagement with His followers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 6, 40, 2, 3, 3, NULL, 'Response to Disturbance', 'Both passages emphasize a reaction of confusion and disturbance among the people. In Acts, the multitude is ''confounded'' by the miraculous speaking, while in Matthew, Herod and Jerusalem are ''troubled'' by the news of Jesus'' birth.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 6, 44, 2, 2, 2, NULL, 'Sound and Multilingual Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of sound in the event of Pentecost. The ''sound from heaven'' in Acts 2:2 precedes the miraculous ability to speak in different languages, as noted in Acts 2:6.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 6, 44, 3, 11, 11, 'the multitude came together', 'Gathering of the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of people in response to miraculous events. In Acts 2:6, the multitude is confounded by hearing their own languages, while in Acts 3:11, the people run together in wonder after witnessing a healing.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 6, 46, 16, 9, 9, 'every man heard them speak', 'Openness to Communication', 'This connection highlights the theme of openness in communication. In Acts, the multitude hears in their own language, while in Corinthians, a ''great door'' is opened, suggesting opportunities for dialogue despite challenges.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 6, 47, 2, 12, 12, NULL, 'Communication of the Gospel', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of effective communication in spreading the gospel. In Acts, the multitude hears in their own language, while in 2 Corinthians, a door is opened for preaching, suggesting opportunities for sharing the message.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 7, 44, 2, 12, 12, 'all amazed', 'Amazement and Doubt in Response', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement of the crowd. The initial wonder in Acts 2:7 leads to further questioning in Acts 2:12, highlighting a shared theme of astonishment and confusion.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 7, 44, 1, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection of Galileans in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of the Galileans. In Acts 2:7, the amazement of the crowd highlights their origin, while Acts 1:11 addresses them directly as ''Ye men of Galilee.'' This connection highlights the significance of their geographical identity in the unfolding events.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 7, 43, 7, 52, 52, 'Galileans', 'Galileans and Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Galileans. Acts 2:7 highlights the amazement at the Galileans speaking, while John 7:52 questions the prophetic significance of Galilee.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 7, 40, 4, 18, 22, 'all these which speak Galileans', 'Connection of Galileans and Fishermen', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Galileans, highlighting the significance of their origin. In Acts, the amazement at the Galileans speaking connects to Jesus calling fishermen from the Sea of Galilee, illustrating their role in the early ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 7, 40, 21, 11, 11, 'Galileans', 'Galileans and Jesus'' Origin', 'This connection highlights the identity of Jesus as a Galilean, as noted in both passages. Acts emphasizes the amazement of the crowd at the Galilean speakers, while Matthew identifies Jesus as ''the prophet of Nazareth of Galilee.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 7, 41, 1, 27, 27, 'they were all amazed', 'Authority and Amazement', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement of the crowd in response to the authority displayed by the speakers. In Acts, the crowd marvels at the Galileans speaking, while in Mark, they are astonished by the authority with which Jesus commands unclean spirits.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 7, 41, 2, 12, 12, 'were all amazed', 'Amazement and Marveling', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of amazement from the people witnessing extraordinary events. In Acts, the amazement is directed towards the Galileans speaking, while in Mark, it is in response to a miraculous healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 2, 9, 60, 1, 1, 1, 'Cappadocia, in Pontus, and Asia', 'Geographical Connections in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize regions such as Pontus and Cappadocia, indicating a shared geographical focus. This connection highlights the dispersion of believers in these areas.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
